dQb5C-UccGIuQH2I1TLtGBcayZFP5g7cmMkGZPcGEmao0_tKtq_mD-b2op9]=E2=80=9D, and =
it was basically about selection effects =E2=80=94 how Twitter selects for =
and promotes the types of people who are inclined to spread political disco=
rd and outrage.=20
At the time, that was just a theory based on personal observation. There ar=
e lots of other ways that social media could create discord and outrage, be=
sides selection effects. These include:
Misreading. Tweets are a highly compressed medium =E2=80=94 just a few line=
s of text, with no real human emotion or space for explanation and nuance =
=E2=80=94 and it=E2=80=99s easy to misinterpret people=E2=80=99s statements=
 in a more negative or aggressive light than they intended.
Pseudonymity. Behind the invincible wall of a pseudonym, people are free to=
 take out all the accumulated frustration, bitterness, resentment, and othe=
r bad feelings that they accumulate from society=E2=80=99s many slights, fr=
ictions, and disappointments =E2=80=94 like cursing at people from inside y=
our car.
Crowd psychology. Psychologists have long theorized [https://email.mg2.subs=
tack.com/c/eJwlkNFuhiAMhZ_m59JQQMELLpYlew2CUJVNwQDuj28_nEnTpj1pTs7nbMUl5Usf=
qVRyN1OvA3XEd9mwVszkLJhN8JopyhkXxGvhQfWKhGLmjLjbsOmaTyTHOW3B2RpSvB94z0VPVk2=
9HEFahQPI2aLylI6DmJAKN8ME4rG1pw8YHWr8xXyliGTTa61HefGPF_tqhbF7h59woA-2S3lpp3=
tv4zOntzdHudyatrRcJGhGGdARmhVTgnfQ0cFO1IFUMwPu-pEhtXPvuZ-k7K20L0H3hXXlnEq17=
qdzaSdZf6eyNuUeXSh3QtOE_YyhXgajnTb0T_j6IPzHYRaMmBtab2zVMHBgwwCCy1E9YRsdASCY=
UoI0R5_aV9Qx2fUIseH7A2ruiIg] that people act differently (and often more ag=
gressively and irrationally) in mobs than in individual interactions. And s=
ocial media is sort of one big free-floating never-ending mob, plus lots of=
 little ad-hoc mobs..=20
In any case, the research results are now rolling in, and we=E2=80=99re sta=
rting to get an idea of how important these various factors are. Both provi=
de general support for my theory that it=E2=80=99s the setup of the platfor=
ms themselves that amplify the worst people in our discourse. But they poin=
t to a more nuanced, complex process than what I initially described.
The Shouting Class: Now, with empirical support!
The first paper [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlUMuOhCAQ_JrhaHipeOCwl=
_kN0kA7sqtgAGfWv19ck05XOpXqSpWDiq-UT72nUsm1TD131BE_ZcVaMZOjYDbBa66o4EISr6Vn=
