JxsZQxlQ2udj9jHkY_wB9epTg], is =E2=80=9CThe Psychology of Online Political =
Hostility: A Comprehensive, Cross-National Test of the Mismatch Hypothesis=
=E2=80=9D, by Alexander Bor and Michael Bang Petersen. Here=E2=80=99s the a=
bstract:
Why are online discussions about politics more hostile than offline discuss=
ions? A popular answer argues that human psychology is tailored for face-to=
-face interaction and people=E2=80=99s behavior therefore changes for the w=
orse in impersonal online discussions. We provide a theoretical formalizati=
on and empirical test of this explanation: the mismatch hypothesis. We argu=
e that mismatches between human psychology and novel features of online env=
ironments could (a) change people=E2=80=99s behavior, (b) create adverse se=
lection effects and (c) bias people=E2=80=99s perceptions. Across eight stu=
dies, leveraging cross-national surveys and behavioral experiments (total N=
=3D8,434), we test the mismatch hypothesis but only find evidence for limit=
ed selection effects. Instead, hostile political discussions are the result=
 of status-driven individuals who are drawn to politics and are equally hos=
tile both online and offline. Finally, we offer initial evidence that onlin=
e discussions feel more hostile, in part, because the behavior of such indi=
viduals is more visible than offline.
The authors=E2=80=99 set of hypotheses doesn=E2=80=99t exactly conform to t=
he breakdown I listed above. They define =E2=80=9Cselection effects=E2=80=
=9D as the idea that more contentious, aggressive people selectively engage=
 in social media politics discussions. In fact, they do find a bit of this =
=E2=80=94 non-hostile people tend not to get involved in political discussi=
ons =E2=80=94 but the effect is true both online and offline.
The paper=E2=80=99s main finding is that the people who are hostile online =
are also hostile in offline discussions. First, they measure this with a bu=
nch of surveys =E2=80=94 basically asking people questions about how hostil=
e they are in various environments, how hostile they perceive other people =
to be, and so on. First of all, they confirm that people generally find onl=
ine discussions to be more hostile than offline ones:
They also find that people report seeing strangers get attacked online much=
 more than offline. So the phenomenon we=E2=80=99re trying to explain here =
is really real; online political discussions really are awful.=20
But when the authors ask people various forms of =E2=80=9Care you an asshol=
e in political discussions=E2=80=9D, they find that the same people who rep=
ort hostile behaviors online tend to report them offline as well. In other =
words, jerks are jerks wherever they are. And the authors correlate this se=
lf-reported jerkiness with self-reported status-seeking behavior =E2=80=94 =
in other words, they think that the Shouting Class is motivated by self-agg=
randizement.
Of course, this could be an artifact of survey methodology =E2=80=94 some p=
eople could just consistently self-report more hostile behavior regardless =
of the context. So the authors also did some experiments. Most importantly,=
 they actually got on Facebook and talked about immigration (the most divis=
ive issue they could think of, sigh [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVU=
EtuxSAMPM1j9yJ-AbJg0U2vETngl9AmEAFplduXNIuqkj-SR_Z4xkHFOeXT7qlUcpWxnjvaiN9l=
xVoxk6NgHoO33FDBhSTeSs9Mb0go4ysjbhBWW_OBZD-mNTioIcVrQfRC9mSxYMAjSq4GVHpwSmv=
He0kHFIOizsNNC4cPGB1a_MJ8pohktUute3mItwd_bxETLHuI7XpXjqlUcJ-dS1tD9pZh28Kcf8=
mfUJ51wWcT8YQp5WtGguWUMzowSgdupOhYRxVM1DFtXpwJ1w8cKbx6L_ykdQ8aHpJuM_9HRrL9S=
GVpyNW6UC7RYwO2I4Z6jhhhWtHfftTb1V-HxhkjtvfQj1AtU4JxpZgUejC3_maYZExyYyRpjD61=
rWj_NP8AuKuPvA]) with some of the people who took the surveys. The people w=
ho reported themselves as being more hostile in online discussions actually=
 were more hostile in online discussions! Score one for survey methodology.=20
Anyway, the authors do a bunch of tests =E2=80=94 surveys and experiments =
=E2=80=94 to see whether non-hostile messages are misread as hostile when t=
hey=E2=80=99re online. They aren=E2=80=99t. In other words, they reject wha=
t I call the =E2=80=9Cmisreading=E2=80=9D hypothesis above.=20
And the finding that it=E2=80=99s just the same people being hostile on- an=
d offline rejects the =E2=80=9Cpseudonymity=E2=80=9D hypothesis too. It doe=
sn=E2=80=99t quite reject the =E2=80=9Ccrowd psychology=E2=80=9D hypothesis=
, because people who are normally nice might perceive themselves as being n=
ice even once they join an angry mob. And as we=E2=80=99ll see with the sec=
ond paper, crowd psychology might well be playing a part in the question of=
 why jerks get more attention online than offline.
But in any case, the authors interpret their findings as support for the id=
ea that I put forth in =E2=80=9CThe Shouting Class=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 that =
the nature of online discussion spaces gives more attention to hostile indi=
viduals than the nature of offline discussion spaces. They put it thus:
But what can explain the hostility gap, if =E2=80=9Cpeople are people=E2=80=
=9D no matter where they discuss? If anti-social personality is the main so=
urce of online (and offline) hostility, the hostility gap is likely to be a=
n artefact of more mechanical effects of online environments=E2=80=99 conne=
ctivity. Online environments are unique in creating large, public forums, w=
here hostile messages may reach thousands including many strangers, could s=
tay accessible perennially and may be promoted by algorithms tuned to gener=
ate interactions=E2=80=A6The hostility gap may thus emerge as a direct cons=
equence of the larger reach of those already motivated to be hostile.
In other words, society has always had about the same number of shouty jerk=
s. But with the rise of social media, we have moved our society=E2=80=99s p=
olitical discussions from spaces in which the shouty jerks were at least so=
mewhat marginalized and contained to spaces that preferentially amplify the=
ir voices.=20
The anger of crowds
The second paper [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkEmOhSAQhk_zWBJmccGi=
N30Nw1Aq3QoGsI23b3wvIUWl_ho_bxssudzmyLWhx0ztPsAkuOoGrUFBZ4UyxWCYJpxxgYIRgWq=
pUazTXAB2GzfTygnoON0WvW0xp6eASy4kWg0lHmZLQTkplfJOgwchvehNZqd7ynusPUOE5MHAH5=
Q7J0CbWVs76ot_vdh3f9d14erfSTiXpUdCjt1SgillqntdteEPWwdSCYqiYYRRMlJCRqYFxxQTZ=
R3xdNAzo9zLkQGxsww8uGGQdrAvQfaF4Xq62qz_xT7vqJifXNeuPB-O9blz6sJ-ptjuCZJ1G4QP=
gvYB-YYyLZCgdMBhss1QxfuSigo-jPpzcmckKBVMa4H6xJB7VTIp2_WIqUP8B9l6iBI] is =E2=
=80=9CHow social learning amplifies moral outrage expression in online soci=
al networks=E2=80=9D, by William J. Brady, Killian McLoughlin, Tuan Doan, a=
nd Molly J. Crockett. Here=E2=80=99s the abstract:
Moral outrage shapes fundamental aspects of social life and is now widespre=
ad in online social networks. Here, we show how social learning processes a=
mplify online moral outrage expressions over time. In two preregistered obs=
ervational studies on Twitter (7331 users and 12.7 million total tweets) an=
d two preregistered behavioral experiments (N =3D 240), we find that positi=
ve social feedback for outrage expressions increases the likelihood of futu=
re outrage expressions, consistent with principles of reinforcement learnin=
g. In addition, users conform their outrage expressions to the expressive n=
orms of their social networks, suggesting norm learning also guides online =
outrage expressions. Norm learning overshadows reinforcement learning when =
normative information is readily observable: in ideologically extreme netwo=
rks, where outrage expression is more common, users are less sensitive to s=
ocial feedback when deciding whether to express outrage. Our findings highl=
ight how platform design interacts with human learning mechanisms to affect=
 moral discourse in digital public spaces.
Now, importantly, this is measuring something different than the first pape=
r =E2=80=94 moral outrage, rather than hostility! So it=E2=80=99s possible =
=E2=80=94 even likely =E2=80=94 that these two papers aren=E2=80=99t actual=
ly explaining the same things. The main result of this paper is that social=
 networks encourage people to act angrier online. But that doesn=E2=80=99t =
necessary encourage them to be meaner.=20
But in any case, this paper is another indication that the structure of soc=
ial media shapes the kind of discussions that happen there.=20
First, they look at people=E2=80=99s Twitter histories, and classify their =
tweets as outraged or non-outraged. They find that when people got more lik=
es for outraged tweets, they tended to write more outraged tweets the next =
day. But when they got more likes for non-outraged tweets, they tended to w=
rite more non-outraged tweets the next day. People respond to incentives an=
d modify their behavior accordingly!=20
They also find that politically extreme people tend to express more outrage=
 (surprise, surprise!), and that people whose Twitter networks are more ext=
reme tend to get rewarded more for outrage, so when you start hanging aroun=
d online with shouters you tend to become a shouter too. Little surprise th=
ere =E2=80=94 this is just classic social group conformity.=20
Also, importantly, they find =E2=80=94 as many others have found =E2=80=94 =
that outrage tends to get more likes on Twitter. They confirm this with an =
experiment =E2=80=94 when they send subjects onto Twitter and tell them to =
try to maximize their likes, they find that outraged tweets get more reward=
ed than non-outraged ones.
All this suggests that over time, Twitter is teaching everyone to express m=
ore outrage, and is helping to turn human society more outraged in general.=
 There are many explanations for the recent period of unrest in America (an=
d the world), but =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just Twitter (and to a lesser exten=
t Facebook)=E2=80=9D has to go on the list here.
Last refuge of scoundrels
Now, it=E2=80=99s worth asking whether the second paper conflicts with the =
first here. The first paper showed that status-seeking hostile political je=
rks are the same people online and offline, while the second paper showed t=
hat Twitter teaches people to act more outraged over time. One possibility =
here is that hostility is simply a very different thing than outrage =E2=80=
=94 the people who go online and start fights and troll and harass are simp=
ly engaged in a different social process from the people who denounce stuff=
=2E In other words, there might actually=
 be a Bullying Class and a Shouting C=
lass, and the latter is more capable than the former of converting new recr=
uits.=20
But I think it=E2=80=99s also possible to see these two behaviors =E2=80=94=
 hostility and outrage =E2=80=94 as part of a single, unified process. And =
it=E2=80=99s what British essayist Samuel Johnson meant in 1775  when he wr=
ote [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkE1uxCAMhU8zLCN-Q7Jg0U0XXVXqARABJ=
6FDIAIyo9y-pJEsW7ZlPb_PmgpLyqfaU6noSrqeO6gI7xKgVsjoKJC1d4oOmFHGkVPckUEMyBc9=
Z4DN-KBqPgDtxxS8NdWneB0wwbhAq3IwSTvP0gnoewJCjJjyeWJCmB5bK29ZczgP0YKCF-QzRUB=
BrbXu5cE-HvSzBcTu7Z9-B-dNl_LSRlffyncKvjbloF--Pa7TrH_MdkDQX2mNJUXkFcWU4JFgPN=
KBs450uDcTtkQOMyXMipECNrNwzE1SCiPNg-NtoV05plKNfXY2bSir31TWtrlK58tlWbfFdkRfT=
w3RTAHcTaPeTP_56AUi5MbaaVMV6RmhDQVnchxu9w0XJ4TTYeCoKbrUrqKKyay7j43nHyqIj6o]=
 that =E2=80=9Cpatriotism is the last refuge of the scoundrel.=E2=80=9D
Johnson was actually talking about insincere expressions of patriotism; wha=
t he meant was that bad people can draw attention away from their bad chara=
cter, and perhaps win acclaim and power for themselves, by professing faux-=
patriotism and thus rallying a whole gang of (true and false) patriots to t=
heir side. I think we can safely extend this idea from national patriotism =
to any sort of group identity where people strongly fight for their group =
=E2=80=94 what American pundits now call =E2=80=9Ctribalism=E2=80=9D (even =
though it=E2=80=99s not the correct anthropological definition of that word=
), and what George Orwell called =E2=80=9Cnationalism=E2=80=9D [https://ema=
il.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkcuOhCAQRb-m2Wl4Ki5YzGZ-w_AoW6ZpMIBj_PvBdjEJAVKHy=
4VbVld4pnyqLZWKrmmu5wYqwlEC1AoZ7QXy7J2iEjPKOHKKOyKFRL7MSwZ4ax9UzTugbTfBW119=
